ican lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Alabama Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Alabama Republicans]]\n[[Category:Alabama lawyers]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American United Methodists]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Huntingdon College alumni]]\n[[Category:Federalist Society members]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Monroe County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mobile, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Selma, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Trump administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Attorneys for the Southern District of Alabama]]\n[[Category:United States Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n", "name_user": "Markdask", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eU.S. Senate campaign (2020):minor syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Sessions"}
{"title_page": "Kheira Hamraoui", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kheira Hamraoui\n| image = 20141015 - PSG-Twente - PSG 01 (cropped) Kheira Hamraoui.jpg\n| caption = Hamraoui in 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|1|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Croix, Nord|Croix]], [[France]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|Barcelona]]\n| clubnumber = 10\n| height = {{height|m=1.78}}<ref>[http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf 2015 World Cup]</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]] \n| years1 = 2006\u20132007 \n| years2 = 2007\u20132008\n| years3 = 2008\u20132012\n| years4 = 2012\u20132016\n| years5 = 2016\u20132018\n| years6 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[CNFE Clairefontaine]] \n| clubs2 = [[FCF H\u00e9nin-Beaumont|H\u00e9nin-Beaumont]] \n| clubs3 = [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne (Ladies)|St.-\u00c9tienne]]\n| clubs4 = [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minines|Paris St-Germain]]\n| clubs5 = [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Lyon]]\n| clubs6 = [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|Barcelona]]\n| caps1 = 11\n| caps2 = 15\n| caps3 = 74\n| caps4 = 55\n| caps5 = 28\n| goals1 = 1\n| goals2 = 5\n| goals3 = 30\n| goals4 = 9\n| goals5 = 7\n| caps6 = 21\n| goals6 = 1\n| nationalteam1 = [[France women's national football team|France]] \n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u2013 \n| nationalcaps1 = 35\n| nationalgoals1 = 3 \n| club-update = 08:05, 8 June 2015 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 4 April 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n[[File:Kheira Hamraoui WCL 2017.jpg|thumb|Hamraoui in 2017 on the field]]\n'''Kheira Hamraoui''' (born 13 January 1990) is a French [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for Spanish club [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|FC Barcelona]].\n\n==Club career==\nHamraoui began her football career with [[CNFE Clairefontaine]], a renowned football academy for female French youth players.<ref name=BarcelonaProfile />\n\nShe's played the majority of her career in the [[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]], for clubs including [[FCF H\u00e9nin-Beaumont|H\u00e9nin-Beaumont]] and [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne (Ladies)|AS Saint-\u00c9tienne]], and [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minine|PSG]].<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=fra/news/newsid=1847311.html PSG women's summer refit]. [[UEFA]], 16 August 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.statsfootofeminin.fr/joueur.php?joueur=59&id=310 Profile] in footofeminin.fr</ref> At St. \u00c9tienne, she was a crucial part of the club's first and only major title win, the [[2010\u201311 Challenge de France|2011 Challenge de France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footofeminin.fr/L-AS-Saint-Etienne-ecrit-une-belle-page-de-sa-jeune-histoire_a3130.html |title=L'AS Saint-Etienne \u00e9crit une belle page de sa jeune histoire |website=footofeminin.fr |publisher=footofeminin.fr |date=21 May 2011 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHamraoui signed for [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Lyon]] from [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minine|PSG]] in 2016 after spending 4 years with the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.womenssoccerunited.com/ol-new-sigings/ |title=Lyon sign Kenza Dali, Kheira Hamraoui, Jessica Houara and Caroline Seger from PSG |website=womenssoccerunited.com |publisher=womenssoccerunited.com |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> It was here that she won two continental [[Treble (association football)|trebles]] by winning the [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Champions League]] twice, winning the [[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]] twice, and finishing first in the [[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]] for two consecutive seasons. In June 2018, she announced her departure from the French league and that she was looking for a new opportunity abroad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Kheira-hamraoui-quitte-l-ol/907721 |title=Kheira Hamraoui quitte l'OL |website=lequipe.fr |publisher= [[L'\u00c9quipe]] |date=4 June 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe left [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Lyon]] in 2018 to sign a two-year contract with [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|FC Barcelona]], her first club venture outside of France.<ref name=BarcelonaProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/womens-football/players/818654/hamraoui/818654/hamraoui |title=Hamraoui |website=fcbarcelona.com |publisher=[[FC Barcelona]] |accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn her first season with the club, she helped them progress to the semifinals of the [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] for the first time. They played [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern]], and Hamraoui bagged an important away goal in the first leg with a low shot to the bottom left corner. In the return leg at the [[Mini Estadi]], Barcelona increased their aggregate score after a goal scored from a penalty, but Hamraoui found herself getting sent off after receiving a second yellow card. Barcelona won 2-0 on aggregate to advance to their first ever UWCL final, but Hamraoui was suspended and was not able to play against her former club.<ref>{{cite web |last1= Jim\u00e9nez |first1= Mayca |url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/05/13/mas_futbol/1557782574_995778.html |title=Kheira Hamraoui se queda sin reencuentro ante el Lyon |website=as.com |publisher= [[Diario AS]] |date=13 May 2019 |accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref> Lyon won the match 4-1.\n\n==International career==\nIn October 2012 she made her debut for the [[France women's national football team|French national team]] in a friendly game against [[England women's national football team|England]].<ref>[http://www.fff.fr/selections/femininesa/actu/543565_hamraoui-ne-pas-faire-qu-une-apparition Hamraoui: \"I don't want to make just one appearance\"]. [[French Football Federation]], 17 October 2012</ref>\n\nShe was part of the French squad at the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]] and the [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Olympics]].\n\nHamraoui has not received a national team call-up since April 2019 and was not selected to the France squad at the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" \n|-\n!colspan=\"7\"|'''Kheira Hamraoui \u2013 goals for {{fbw|FRA}}'''\n|- \n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 1. || 11 April 2016 || [[Stade Nungesser]], [[Valenciennes]], [[France]] || {{fbw|UKR}} ||align=\"center\"| '''1'''\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 4\u20130 || rowspan=3|[[UEFA Women's Euro 2017 qualifying Group 3|UEFA Women's Euro 2017 qualifying]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 2. || rowspan=2| 30 September 2016|| rowspan=2|[[Stade S\u00e9bastien Charl\u00e9ty]], [[Paris]], [[France]] || rowspan=2|{{fbw|ALB}} ||align=center| '''2'''\u20130 ||rowspan=2 align=center| 6\u20130 \n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 3. || align=center|'''4'''\u20130 \n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|<small>''Correct as of 4 April 2019''</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statsfootofeminin.fr/selection/joueur.php?joueur=59&id=1 |title=Equipe de France A - Kheira Hamraoui |publisher=footofeminin.fr |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n===Club===\n====AS St. Etienne====\n*[[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]]: Winner- [[2010\u201311 Challenge de France|2011]]\n\n====Paris Saint-Germain====\n*[[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]]: Runner-up- 2014\n\n====Olympique Lyonnais====\n*[[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]]: Winner- [[2016\u201317 Division 1 F\u00e9minine|2016-2017]], [[2017\u201318 Division 1 F\u00e9minine|2017-2018]]\n*[[UEFA Women's Champions League]]: Winner- [[2016\u201317 UEFA Women's Champions League|2017]], [[2017\u201318 UEFA Women's Champions League|2018]]\n*[[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]]: Winner- 2017, 2018\n\n====FC Barcelona====\n*[[UEFA Women's Champions League]]: Runner-up- [[2018\u201319 UEFA Women's Champions League|2019]]\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a Femenina]]: Winner- [[2019\u201320 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a Femenina|2020]]\n\n===France===\n*[[Cyprus Cup]]: Winner, [[2014 Cyprus Cup|2014]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{FC Barcelona (women) squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| bg          = #0055A4\n| fg          = #FFFFFF\n| bordercolor = #EF4135\n| title = France squads\n| list1 =\n{{France squad 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{France women's football squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamraoui, Kheira}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Croix, Nord]]\n[[Category:French women's footballers]]\n[[Category:France women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minine players]]\n[[Category:AS Saint-\u00c9tienne (women) players]]\n[[Category:CNFE Clairefontaine players]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:2015 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:French people of Algerian descent]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of France]]\n[[Category:Division 1 F\u00e9minine players]]\n[[Category:Women's Olympic footballers of France]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Nord (French department)]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed players]]\n[[Category:Primera Divisi\u00f3n (women) players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kheira Hamraoui\n| image = 20141015 - PSG-Twente - PSG 01 (cropped) Kheira Hamraoui.jpg\n| caption = Hamraoui in 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|1|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Croix, Nord|Croix]], [[France]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|Barcelona]]\n| clubnumber = 10\n| height = {{height|m=1.78}}<ref>[http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf 2015 World Cup]</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]] \n| years1 = 2006\u20132007 \n| years2 = 2007\u20132008\n| years3 = 2008\u20132012\n| years4 = 2012\u20132016\n| years5 = 2016\u20132018\n| years6 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[CNFE Clairefontaine]] \n| clubs2 = [[FCF H\u00e9nin-Beaumont|H\u00e9nin-Beaumont]] \n| clubs3 = [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne (Ladies)|St.-\u00c9tienne]]\n| clubs4 = [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minines|Paris St-Germain]]\n| clubs5 = [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Lyon]]\n| clubs6 = [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|Barcelona]]\n| caps1 = 11\n| caps2 = 15\n| caps3 = 74\n| caps4 = 55\n| caps5 = 28\n| goals1 = 1\n| goals2 = 5\n| goals3 = 30\n| goals4 = 9\n| goals5 = 7\n| caps6 = 21\n| goals6 = 1\n| nationalteam1 = [[France women's national football team|France]] \n| nationalyears1 = 2012\u2013 \n| nationalcaps1 = 35\n| nationalgoals1 = 3 \n| club-update = 08:05, 8 June 2015 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 4 April 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n[[File:Kheira Hamraoui WCL 2017.jpg|thumb|Hamraoui in 2017 on the field]]\n'''Kheira Hamraoui''' (born 13 January 1990) is a French [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for Spanish club [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|FC Barcelona]].\n\n==Club career==\nHamraoui began her football career with [[CNFE Clairefontaine]], a renowned football academy for female French youth players.<ref name=BarcelonaProfile></ref>\n\nShe's played the majority of her career in the [[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]], for clubs including [[FCF H\u00e9nin-Beaumont|H\u00e9nin-Beaumont]] and [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne (Ladies)|AS Saint-\u00c9tienne]], and [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minine|PSG]].<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=fra/news/newsid=1847311.html PSG women's summer refit]. [[UEFA]], 16 August 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.statsfootofeminin.fr/joueur.php?joueur=59&id=310 Profile] in footofeminin.fr</ref> At St. \u00c9tienne, she was a crucial part of the club's first and only major title win, the [[2010\u201311 Challenge de France|2011 Challenge de France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footofeminin.fr/L-AS-Saint-Etienne-ecrit-une-belle-page-de-sa-jeune-histoire_a3130.html |title=L'AS Saint-Etienne \u00e9crit une belle page de sa jeune histoire |website=footofeminin.fr |publisher=footofeminin.fr |date=21 May 2011 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHamraoui signed for [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Lyon]] from [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minine|PSG]] in 2016 after spending 4 years with the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.womenssoccerunited.com/ol-new-sigings/ |title=Lyon sign Kenza Dali, Kheira Hamraoui, Jessica Houara and Caroline Seger from PSG |website=womenssoccerunited.com |publisher=womenssoccerunited.com |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> It was here that she won two continental [[Treble (association football)|trebles]] by winning the [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Champions League]] twice, winning the [[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]] twice, and finishing first in the [[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]] for two consecutive seasons. In June of 2018, she announced her departure from the French league and that she was looking for a new opportunity abroad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Kheira-hamraoui-quitte-l-ol/907721 |title=Kheira Hamraoui quitte l'OL |website=lequipe.fr |publisher= [[L'\u00c9quipe]] |date=4 June 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe left [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Lyon]] in 2018 to sign a two-year contract with [[FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed|FC Barcelona]], her first club venture outside of France.<ref name=BarcelonaProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/womens-football/players/818654/hamraoui/818654/hamraoui |title=Hamraoui |website=fcbarcelona.com |publisher=[[FC Barcelona]] |accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn her first season with the club, she helped them progress to the semifinals of the [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] for the first time. They played [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern]], and Hamraoui bagged an important away goal in the first leg with a low shot to the bottom left corner. In the return leg at the [[Mini Estadi]], Barcelona increased their aggregate score after a goal scored from a penalty, but Hamraoui found herself getting sent off after receiving a second yellow card. Barcelona won 2-0 on aggregate to advance to their first ever UWCL final, but Hamraoui was suspended and was not able to play against her former club.<ref>{{cite web |last1= Jim\u00e9nez |first1= Mayca |url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/05/13/mas_futbol/1557782574_995778.html |title=Kheira Hamraoui se queda sin reencuentro ante el Lyon |website=as.com |publisher= [[Diario AS]] |date=13 May 2019 |accessdate= 4 April 2020}}</ref> Lyon won the match 4-1.\n\n==International career==\nIn October 2012 she made her debut for the [[France women's national football team|French national team]] in a friendly game against [[England women's national football team|England]].<ref>[http://www.fff.fr/selections/femininesa/actu/543565_hamraoui-ne-pas-faire-qu-une-apparition Hamraoui: \"I don't want to make just one appearance\"]. [[French Football Federation]], 17 October 2012</ref>\n\nShe was part of the French squad at the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]] and the [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Olympics]]. \n\nHamraoui has not received a national team call-up since April 2019 and was not selected to the France squad at the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" \n|-\n!colspan=\"7\"|'''Kheira Hamraoui \u2013 goals for {{fbw|FRA}}'''\n|- \n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 1. || 11 April 2016 || [[Stade Nungesser]], [[Valenciennes]], [[France]] || {{fbw|UKR}} ||align=\"center\"| '''1'''\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 4\u20130 || rowspan=3|[[UEFA Women's Euro 2017 qualifying Group 3|UEFA Women's Euro 2017 qualifying]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 2. || rowspan=2| 30 September 2016|| rowspan=2|[[Stade S\u00e9bastien Charl\u00e9ty]], [[Paris]], [[France]] || rowspan=2|{{fbw|ALB}} ||align=center| '''2'''\u20130 ||rowspan=2 align=center| 6\u20130 \n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 3. || align=center|'''4'''\u20130 \n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|<small>''Correct as of 4 April 2019''</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statsfootofeminin.fr/selection/joueur.php?joueur=59&id=1 |title=Equipe de France A - Kheira Hamraoui |publisher=footofeminin.fr |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n===Club===\n====AS St. Etienne====\n*[[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]]: Winner- [[2010\u201311 Challenge de France|2011]]\n\n====Paris Saint-Germain====\n*[[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]]: Runner-up- 2014\n\n====Olympique Lyonnais====\n*[[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]]: Winner- [[2016\u201317 Division 1 F\u00e9minine|2016-2017]], [[2017\u201318 Division 1 F\u00e9minine|2017-2018]]\n*[[UEFA Women's Champions League]]: Winner- [[2016\u201317 UEFA Women's Champions League|2017]], [[2017\u201318 UEFA Women's Champions League|2018]]\n*[[Coupe de France F\u00e9minine]]: Winner- 2017, 2018\n\n====FC Barcelona====\n*[[UEFA Women's Champions League]]: Runner-up- [[2018\u201319 UEFA Women's Champions League|2019]]\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a Femenina]]: Winner- [[2019\u201320 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a Femenina|2020]]\n\n===France===\n*[[Cyprus Cup]]: Winner, [[2014 Cyprus Cup|2014]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{FC Barcelona (women) squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| bg          = #0055A4\n| fg          = #FFFFFF\n| bordercolor = #EF4135\n| title = France squads\n| list1 =\n{{France squad 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{France women's football squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamraoui, Kheira}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Croix, Nord]]\n[[Category:French women's footballers]]\n[[Category:France women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minine players]]\n[[Category:AS Saint-\u00c9tienne (women) players]]\n[[Category:CNFE Clairefontaine players]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:2015 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:French people of Algerian descent]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of France]]\n[[Category:Division 1 F\u00e9minine players]]\n[[Category:Women's Olympic footballers of France]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Nord (French department)]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona Femen\u00ed players]]\n[[Category:Primera Divisi\u00f3n (women) players]]\n\n\n{{France-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kheira_Hamraoui"}
